    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Asterias squamata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1615",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tiny, inconspicuous, plain white to pale grey species that is easily missed, or assumed to be a juvenile, but is in fact extremely common. Disc round, its upper surface covered in overlapping rings of scales. Radial shields D-shaped and abut one another along their full length. Arms relatively short, thin and fragile with obvious but fairly-short laterally projecting spines. Despite the tiny size broods live young.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1616",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Arm length up to 10 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1617",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Extremely widespread across Atlantic, Pacific and Indian Oceans, Mediterranean, Red Sea, etc. (in fact represents a species complex with separate forms in various different regions).</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to Mozambique.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1618",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Very common from the intertidal to depths of about 2000 m. Coastal specimens usually among gravel or course sand, or under rocks. Known to be luminescent but the function of this is not well understood.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1619",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Feeds on small detrital particles picked up from the sediment surface and passed to the mouth by the tube feet.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1620",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Hermaphroditic and despite its small body size broods the young. Analysis of scanned specimens from South Africa showed an <i>A. squamata </i>to contain 6 developing embryos, which together made up about 24% of the disc volume.&nbsp; This was much more than in a specimen of the other, much larger, brooding species - <i>Ophioderma wahlbergii</i>, where 13 brooded young together made up only 14% of disc volume. The young lie with the mouth upwards and pressed against the body wall of the mother and their large size can only be explained by the fact that they obtain nutrition directly from the mother.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1621",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The small adult size, plain colour and appressed radial shields distinguish this species from other common coastal brittlestars in the region. A second similar species <i>A. strata</i> is also found in deeper waters but microscopic examination is needed to distinguish these species (see Olbers reference below for details of how to do this).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1622",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2022). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 232).<br><br>Clark, AM & Courtman-Stock, J (1976). The Echinoderms of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History), London (p. 151).<br><br>Landschoff, J & Griffiths, CL (2015). Three-dimensional visualisation of brooding behaviour in two distantly related brittle stars from South African waters. <i>African Journal of Marine Science</i>, 37(4), 533-541.<br><br>Olbers, JM, Griffiths, CL, O'Hara, TD & Samyn, Y (2019). Field guide to the brittle and basket stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) of South Africa. <i>ABC Taxa</i>, 19, 1–346 (p. 217).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1623",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
